2. Binary Search
Definition

Searches by repeatedly dividing the sorted array into two halves.

Condition: Array must be sorted.

Time Complexity
Best Case: O(1)
Average Case: O(log n)
Worst Case: O(log n)
Space Complexity
O(1) (Iterative)


Java Code

import java.util.Scanner;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        int n = sc.nextInt();
        int[] arr = new int[n];

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
            arr[i] = sc.nextInt();

        int key = sc.nextInt();

        int low = 0;
        int high = n - 1;

        while (low <= high) {
            int mid = (low + high) / 2;

            if (arr[mid] == key) {
                System.out.println("Found at index " + mid);
                return;
            } else if (arr[mid] < key) {
                low = mid + 1;
            } else {
                high = mid - 1;
            }
        }

        System.out.println("Not Found");
    }
}
Input
5
10 20 30 40 50
40
Output
Found at index 3


Linear Search vs Binary Search
Feature	Linear Search	Binary Search
Array Type	Sorted/Unsorted	Sorted Only
Time Complexity	O(n)	O(log n)
Space Complexity	O(1)	O(1)
Speed	Slower	Faster
Exam Points
Linear Search: Checks elements one by one.
Binary Search: Works only on sorted arrays.
Linear Search Time: O(n)
Binary Search Time: O(log n)
Both Space Complexity: O(1) (iterative)



